 an initial collective identity within the Iberian Peninsula from the Middle Ages to the end of the ancien regime based on the Catholic religion, loyalty to the Crown and Empire. The adaptation of this identity to the modern era, beginning with the Napoleonic Wars and the liberal revolutions, forms the crux of this study. None the less, the book also embraces the highly contested evolution of the national identity in the twentieth century, including both the Civil War and the Franco Dictatorship. Álvarez-Junco´s pioneering study was awarded both the National Prize for Literature in Spain and the Fastenrath Prize by the Spanish Royal Academy  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGroup identity -- Spain. 0aNational characteristics, Spanish. 0aNationalism -- Spain -- History -- 19th century. 0aSpain -- Politics and government -- 19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Spain & Portugal.2bisacsh  aBasque Country.  aCatalonia.  aIberian Peninsula.  aMiddle Ages.  aSpanish national identity.  aancien regime.  acollective identity.  aidea of Spain.  anational consciousness.  asub-nationalism.1 aÁlvarez-Junco, José, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779477240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847794772423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847794772/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles